In the [[Royal Navy]], a '''Divisional Transport Officer (DTO)''' or a '''Divisional Naval Transport Officer (DNTO)''' and later called a '''Divisional Sea Transport Officer (DSTO)''' <ref>{{cite book |last1=Titterton |first1=G. A. |title=The Royal Navy and the Mediterranean |date=2002 |publisher=Psychology Press |location=Cambridge, England |isbn=9780714651798 |page=viii |url=https://books.google.lk/books?id=hS_895OalVAC&pg=PR32&lpg=PR32&dq=Divisional+Sea+Transport+Officer+(DSTO)&source=bl&ots=9XT2SkIfZo&sig=1ME6ji34a0W3gCvjGduZ8lxFpXc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjHtqOKnuzdAhXQdysKHdn3CzsQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Divisional%20Sea%20Transport%20Officer%20(DSTO)&f=false |language=en |chapter=Abbreviations}}</ref> is a shore-based [[Naval Officer|naval officer]] responsible for the efficient working of the transports and boats of the flotilla, division or squadron under his charge. <ref>{{cite book |last1=War Office |first1=The |title=Field service pocket book, 1914 |date=1914 |publisher=London : printed under the authority of H.M.S.O. by Harrison & Sons |location=London, England |page=80 |url=https://archive.org/details/b28998558/page/96}}</ref>
==History== The Royal Navy established a Naval Transports Service on 22 December 1916 <ref>{{cite book |last1=Great Britain |first1=Admiralty The |title=The Orders in Council for the Regulation of the Naval Service |date=1928 |publisher=Harrison and Sons |location=London England |page=459 |language=en}}</ref> during World War I the [[Rear-Admiral Commanding, British Aegean Squadron]] had a divisional transport officer based at [[Salonika]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harley |first1=Simon |last2=Lovell |first2=Tony |title=Salonika - The Dreadnought Project |url=http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Salonika |website=www.dreadnoughtproject.org |publisher=Harley and Lovell |accessdate=3 October 2018 |language=en |date=23 August 2018}}</ref> These officers were part of the Naval Transport Service.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mace |first1=Martin |title=The Royal Navy and the War at Sea 1914-1919 |date=2014 |publisher=Pen and Sword |location=Barnsley, England |isbn=9781781593172 |page=171 |url=https://books.google.lk/books?id=LpiPBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA171&dq=the+royal+navy+transport+service&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJ3L292OrdAhXLtI8KHcbwBsMQ6AEITzAH#v=onepage&q=the%20royal%20navy%20transport%20service&f=false |language=en}}</ref> In 1921 the Naval Transport Service was renamed the Sea Transport Service.<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacFarlane |first1=John M. |title=British Naval Reserve Organizations |url=http://www.nauticapedia.ca/Articles/British_Naval_Reserve_Orgs.php |website=www.nauticapedia.ca |accessdate=3 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>
